yle="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">rmation on complaints received;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How effectively complaints handling is lead within government; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How complaints are being used to drive innovation and service improvement.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Bearing in mind the findings of the Health Select Committee two years ago which reported </span><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/health-committee/news/11-06-28-clreoprt-substantive-/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/health-committee/news/11-06-28-clreoprt-substantive-/</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> I can only offer my experience of NHS Complaints.</span></p><h1 style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt; font-weight:normal">“The NHS complaints system is not working, says Commons Health Committee”</span></h1><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Using your guidance: </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How departments record and provide </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">info</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">rmation on complaints received</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Information is collected</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> reviewed and then either refused or sent to “reconsideration” for a few months ….then often refused! </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I believe the system is set up to fail complainants and the term “local resolution” is more often a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> request to “escalate to PHSO “if not happy”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">referral to PHSO </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">needs more than “if not happy”  as I know to my cost!</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I realise you don’t investigate individual complaints and my experience of PHSO process is what I need to convey:</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a) there was no investigation as “not enough records” </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(isn’t that a reason to investigate?)</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">b) A case worker left during assessing my case and left a note on file of “unremedied Injustice” This has been routinely ignored.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c) Recent access to email conversations from SHA SUI Investigation Manager clearly shows the Investigation manager lied re my “alleged agreement ” on the Terms of Reference for the SUI Investigation into my sons death in hospital. This investigation was offered 6 years later and at no time was the PHSO office seeking my advice on anything! </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d) Dame Julie Mellor asked me to a meeting with her to discuss Baroness Fritchies Report.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><a href="http://www.ombudsman.org.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0008/19664/Fritchie_report_FINAL.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.ombudsman.org.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0008/19664/Fritchie_report_FINAL.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> I agreed and was advised that restrictions would be placed on the meeting re what we could discuss. I was told </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I couldn’t discuss any</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">thing re my sons experience (which is why I am still here) and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I refused to attend. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">I wonder how many others </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">closed down too.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e) I wrote to PHSO on November 17</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 2012 to state why I needed to retain my democratic right to question policy and process and since then one reply dated 14</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> February 2013 telling me “we will not be revisiting this decision and theres nothing more I can add” I ‘m sorry but the case remains closed. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">I wonder how many others told this too?  </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How effectively complaints handlin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">g is lead within government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I refer you to the Health Select Committee Report which states “NHS Complaints system is not working”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Still! </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">One point is it costs in the region of £32m per year for the PHSO process but less than 2% of complaints are investigated. Is this because PHSO is working on other areas eg as with Equitable Life?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How complaints are being used to drive innovation and service improvement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In my opinion </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and from 8 years experience in NHS Complaints, Complaints are not being used to drive innovation and service improvement.. There is a woeful lack of integrity and many are taking full advantage of the fact complaints are seen in such a poor light.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">June 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p 